"1240":"1240","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1315":"1315","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1246":"1246","1255":"1255","about 1255":"about 1255","1208":"1208","england":"England","Alsace/Lorriane, France":"Alsace, France","Ollantigh Manor, Ollantigh, Wye, Ashford, Kent England":"Wye, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"KEMP","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: status name for a champion, Middle English and Middle Low German <i>kempe</i>. In the Middle Ages a champion was a professional fighter on behalf of others; for example the King's Champion, at the coronation, had the duty of issuing a general challenge to battle to anyone who denied the king's right to the throne. The Middle English word corresponds to Old English <i>cempa</i> and Old Norse <i>kempa</i> ‘warrior’; both these go back to ancient Germanic <i>campo</i> ‘warrior’, which is the source of the Dutch and North German name, corresponding to High German   Kampf  .","Dutch and North German (North Rhine-Westphalia): from the personal name <i>Kempe</i>, <i>Kampe</i>; see 1 above.","Dutch and Flemish: metonymic occupational name for someone who grew or processed hemp, from Middle Dutch <i>canep</i> ‘hemp’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kampf","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (mainly <b>Kämpf</b>): from Middle High German <i>kampf</i>, German <i>Kamf</i> ‘fight, struggle’, hence an occupational name for a champion, a professional fighter (see   Kemp  ), or a nickname for someone with a pugnacious temperament. As a Jewish name it can be artificial. Compare   Kaempf  .","German: extended form of   Kamp   1."]},{"name":"Kemps","meanings":["Dutch and Flemish: genitivized form of   Kemp   2 or 4, concentrated in North Brabant and adjacent northern Belgium.","English (London): variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempt","meanings":["Scottish and English: perhaps from a shortened form of the extinct Scottish surname <i>Kemptie</i>, of uncertain origin, or an altered form of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Ilse.  Scandinavian Detlev, Gunhild.","English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempel","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempke","meanings":["North German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempker","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempkes","meanings":["North German and Dutch: genitivized pet form of   Kemp   2. Particularly in North Rhine-Westphalia and adjacent Gelderland."]},{"name":"Kempner","meanings":["German:","occupational name for a champion at jousting or wrestling, an agent derivative of <i>Kempe</i> ‘fight’ (see   Kemp  ).","habitational name, with agent suffix <i>-er</i>, for someone from any of various places called Kempen (notably near Krefeld) or from Kempno near Poznań, Poland."]}]},{"name":"Amila","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Peaceful, secure’; name of the Prophet's mother."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":23,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":54,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Amila KEMP was born in 1236, in England, United Kingdom, her father, James KEMP, was 28 and